In the world of today, everyone will have to do presentations at some point of their life, whether
for a simple book presentation in primary school or maybe a quarterly report in your firm, or
be it giving your third lecture of the day. Seeing as presentations are a common occurrence in
the lives of many people, one would imagine that the way to give these presentations is very
optimised, but when starting this thesis, it seemed to us that this was not the case, seeing as
through interactions with lecturers and through courses on presentations I have heard time and
again that interacting with your audience is important, as well as using gestures, or many other
presenting techniques, but when we look at the presentations we see most often in our day to
day lives it seems that many presenters are simply chained to a desk or podium, because they
have to use the arrow keys on the laptop to control their slides.
This then brought us to a few questions, the first of which being of course whether this is in fact
a problem that presenters have, and the second of which being whether we could create a system
to fix this problem in the case that it was one. To solve the first question, we started by doing a
survey, asking people questions like how often they presented, what presentation tools they used
and whether they have had any issues from using these. From this survey we then noted that
PowerPoint still seems to be the leading presentation software and that most people simply use
their laptop and nothing else to present. One thing to note however is that while many people
claim that they have no issues with the way they present currently, these same people will then
also say that they would be very open to have a tool that offers them extra functionality, with
them giving their own suggestions as to what needs they have that their current setup does not
meet as well as they would like.
From these needs and current existing related work, we then started by designing our prototypes,
followed by evaluating them, both by going through iterations ourselves and brainstorming issues
that could still be solved, as well as asking fellow students what they thought of them and what
suggestions they had for making it better or more usable. Once a rigid prototype was established,
we started working on making this prototype a reality, and during the implementation phase,
other evolutions of the prototype followed, both through finding flaws and through finding new
ideas that could still be added.
After finishing this prototype, we did a new survey as well as a user study to find out whether
our implementation is sound and usable, whether it helps with presenting, and whether or not
users feel like there are still things that could be improved.